## The problem — reads and writes fighting each other

```text
Single orders table:
  Orders dashboard query: 50 complex JOINs, GROUP BY, ORDER BY → adds indexes
  Order placement write: INSERT + UPDATE → those indexes slow every write
  Reporting query: SELECT with date ranges → causes lock contention during high writes

Result:
  Adding read-friendly indexes → write throughput drops 30%
  Adding write-optimized structure → queries run 5x slower
  Both sides are compromised
```

---

## Understanding CQRS

```text
CQRS = Command Query Responsibility Segregation

Command side (writes):
  - Handles: PlaceOrderCommand, CancelOrderCommand, UpdateStatusCommand
  - Optimized for: consistency, validation, business rules
  - Data store: normalized PostgreSQL (or event store)

Query side (reads):
  - Handles: GetOrderById, GetOrdersByUser, GetOrderDashboard
  - Optimized for: speed, denormalized views, specific use cases
  - Data store: read-optimized (read replica, Redis, Elasticsearch, separate DB)

Key insight: the read model is a different data structure from the write model.
You maintain both — writes update the write side, which then syncs to the read side.
```

---

## Implementation: CQRS with Spring Boot + Kafka

### Step 1: Command side — write model

```java
// Commands are plain objects expressing intent
@Value
@Builder
public class PlaceOrderCommand {
    UUID orderId;         // generated by caller (enables idempotency)
    Long userId;
    List<OrderItem> items;
    BigDecimal totalAmount;
}

@Value
@Builder
public class CancelOrderCommand {
    UUID orderId;
    String reason;
}

// Command handler — validates business rules, persists, publishes event
@Service
@RequiredArgsConstructor
public class OrderCommandHandler {

    private final OrderRepository orderRepo;         // write DB
    private final KafkaTemplate<String, Object> kafka;

    @Transactional
    public void handle(PlaceOrderCommand cmd) {
        // Business rule validation
        if (cmd.getItems().isEmpty()) {
            throw new InvalidOrderException("Order must have at least one item");
        }
        if (orderRepo.existsById(cmd.getOrderId())) {
            log.info("Duplicate order command {} — idempotent, skipping", cmd.getOrderId());
            return;
        }

        // Persist write model
        Order order = Order.builder()
            .id(cmd.getOrderId())
            .userId(cmd.getUserId())
            .items(cmd.getItems())
            .totalAmount(cmd.getTotalAmount())
            .status(OrderStatus.PLACED)
            .placedAt(Instant.now())
            .build();
        orderRepo.save(order);

        // Publish domain event — query side will consume and update its view
        kafka.send("order.events", cmd.getOrderId().toString(),
            new OrderPlacedEvent(cmd.getOrderId(), cmd.getUserId(),
                cmd.getItems(), cmd.getTotalAmount(), order.getPlacedAt()));

        log.info("Order {} placed — event published to update read model", cmd.getOrderId());
    }

    @Transactional
    public void handle(CancelOrderCommand cmd) {
        Order order = orderRepo.findById(cmd.getOrderId())
            .orElseThrow(() -> new OrderNotFoundException(cmd.getOrderId()));

        if (order.getStatus() == OrderStatus.SHIPPED) {
            throw new InvalidOrderStateException("Cannot cancel shipped order");
        }

        order.setStatus(OrderStatus.CANCELLED);
        order.setCancelledAt(Instant.now());
        order.setCancellationReason(cmd.getReason());
        orderRepo.save(order);

        kafka.send("order.events", cmd.getOrderId().toString(),
            new OrderCancelledEvent(cmd.getOrderId(), cmd.getReason()));
    }
}
```

### Step 2: Query side — read model (denormalized for fast reads)

```java
// Read model is shaped for the UI — denormalized, pre-joined
@Document(indexName = "order_views")  // Elasticsearch for search queries
@Data
@Builder
public class OrderView {
    String orderId;
    Long userId;
    String userEmail;          // denormalized from user service
    String userFullName;       // denormalized
    List<OrderItemView> items; // denormalized item details
    String status;
    BigDecimal totalAmount;
    Instant placedAt;
    Instant updatedAt;
    // All data in ONE document — zero JOINs at read time
}

// Read model is built by consuming write events
@Component
@RequiredArgsConstructor
public class OrderViewProjection {

    private final OrderViewRepository viewRepo;  // Elasticsearch or separate PostgreSQL
    private final UserService userService;

    @KafkaListener(topics = "order.events", groupId = "order-view-projector")
    public void project(OrderPlacedEvent event) {
        // Fetch user info to denormalize into the view
        User user = userService.getUser(event.getUserId());

        OrderView view = OrderView.builder()
            .orderId(event.getOrderId().toString())
            .userId(event.getUserId())
            .userEmail(user.getEmail())
            .userFullName(user.getFullName())
            .items(event.getItems().stream().map(OrderItemView::from).toList())
            .status("PLACED")
            .totalAmount(event.getTotalAmount())
            .placedAt(event.getPlacedAt())
            .build();
        viewRepo.save(view);

        log.info("Read model updated for order {}", event.getOrderId());
    }

    @KafkaListener(topics = "order.events", groupId = "order-view-projector")
    public void project(OrderCancelledEvent event) {
        viewRepo.findById(event.getOrderId().toString()).ifPresent(view -> {
            view.setStatus("CANCELLED");
            view.setUpdatedAt(Instant.now());
            viewRepo.save(view);
        });
    }
}
```

### Step 3: Query handler — reads only from the read model

```java
@Service
@RequiredArgsConstructor
public class OrderQueryHandler {

    private final OrderViewRepository viewRepo;

    // Simple, fast lookup — no JOINs, pre-denormalized
    public OrderView getOrder(UUID orderId) {
        return viewRepo.findById(orderId.toString())
            .orElseThrow(() -> new OrderNotFoundException(orderId));
    }

    // Full-text search, filter, sort — all from read model
    public Page<OrderView> searchOrders(OrderSearchRequest request) {
        return viewRepo.findByStatusAndPlacedAtBetween(
            request.getStatus(),
            request.getFrom(),
            request.getTo(),
            PageRequest.of(request.getPage(), request.getSize(),
                Sort.by("placedAt").descending()));
    }

    // Dashboard aggregations — no complex SQL
    public OrderDashboard getDashboard(Long userId) {
        List<OrderView> orders = viewRepo.findByUserId(userId);
        return OrderDashboard.builder()
            .totalOrders(orders.size())
            .totalSpent(orders.stream().map(OrderView::getTotalAmount)
                .reduce(BigDecimal.ZERO, BigDecimal::add))
            .pendingOrders(orders.stream().filter(o -> "PLACED".equals(o.getStatus())).count())
            .build();
    }
}
```

---

## What changes after CQRS

```text
BEFORE CQRS:
  Write: INSERT into orders (heavy indexes) → 120ms
  Dashboard query: SELECT with 8 JOINs → 4.2 seconds

AFTER CQRS:
  Write: INSERT into orders (minimal indexes, write-optimized) → 45ms
  Dashboard query: read from OrderView (pre-joined Elasticsearch doc) → 12ms
  Trade-off: 100-200ms eventual consistency lag between write and read model
```

---

## Event Sourcing — store events instead of state

Take CQRS further: instead of persisting the Order entity's current state, persist every event that changed it.

```java
// Event store — append-only log of order events
@Entity
@Table(name = "order_events")
@Data
public class StoredEvent {
    @Id
    @GeneratedValue
    private Long sequenceNumber;   // global ordering
    private UUID aggregateId;      // order ID
    private String eventType;      // "OrderPlacedEvent"
    @Column(columnDefinition = "jsonb")
    private String payload;        // full event as JSON
    private Instant occurredAt;
}

// Replay all events to reconstruct current order state
public Order reconstructOrder(UUID orderId) {
    List<StoredEvent> events = eventStore.findByAggregateIdOrderBySequence(orderId);
    Order order = new Order();  // start empty
    for (StoredEvent e : events) {
        order.apply(deserialize(e));  // each event mutates state
    }
    return order;  // fully reconstructed from event history
}
```

**When to use Event Sourcing:**
- Audit requirements ("show me every change to this order ever")
- Temporal queries ("what did the order state look like at 3 PM yesterday?")
- Debugging in production ("replay exact sequence of events that caused the bug")
- Complex domains with rich history (banking, compliance, insurance)

**When NOT to use Event Sourcing:**
- Simple CRUD apps — massive over-engineering
- When you just want CQRS for performance — Event Sourcing is a separate concern

---

## Your interview answer

> "I separated the read and write models using CQRS. The write side has a normalized orders table optimized for transactional writes with minimal indexes. On every write, a domain event is published to Kafka. A projection consumer builds a denormalized read model (OrderView in Elasticsearch) that has all the data the UI needs in one document — no JOINs at read time. Dashboard queries went from 4 seconds to 12ms. The trade-off is ~100-200ms eventual consistency lag between writes and the read model, which is acceptable for our dashboard use case. We didn't add Event Sourcing since we don't have audit requirements."

followUps.answer:
When a user places an order, the write model is updated immediately. But the read model (OrderView) is only updated after the Kafka consumer processes the event — which takes 50-500ms depending on load.

```text
t=0ms:   User places order → write model saves it, 201 returned to user
t=150ms: Kafka consumer processes OrderPlacedEvent → updates read model
t=200ms: User refreshes order history → sees the new order

But at t=10ms, if user immediately hits 'refresh':
  GET /api/orders/my-orders → reads from read model → order NOT YET THERE
  → User thinks the order didn't go through!
```

**Fix 1 — Return order data in the 201 response** (not from read model):
```java
@PostMapping("/api/orders")
public ResponseEntity<OrderResponse> placeOrder(...) {
    UUID orderId = commandHandler.handle(cmd);
    // Return the just-created order directly — don't read from read model!
    return ResponseEntity.status(201)
        .body(OrderResponse.from(orderId, cmd));
}
```

**Fix 2 — Read-your-own-writes with a write-side lookup for brief window:**
```java
public OrderView getOrder(UUID orderId, boolean allowWriteFallback) {
    OrderView view = viewRepo.findById(orderId.toString()).orElse(null);
    if (view == null && allowWriteFallback) {
        // Read model not updated yet — fall back to write model
        Order order = orderRepo.findById(orderId).orElseThrow();
        return OrderView.from(order);  // temporary, may be slightly less denormalized
    }
    return view;
}
```

**Fix 3 — UI optimistic update**: Show the new order in the UI immediately using the data the client already has (before read model confirms).

One of the key advantages of Event Sourcing + CQRS: you can always rebuild the read model by replaying all events.

**With Event Sourcing (events stored in DB):**
```java
@Service
public class ReadModelRebuilder {

    @Transactional
    public void rebuild() {
        log.info("Starting read model rebuild...");

        // Clear current read model
        orderViewRepo.deleteAll();

        // Replay ALL events from the beginning
        long processedCount = 0;
        Page<StoredEvent> page;
        int pageNum = 0;

        do {
            page = eventStore.findAllOrderBySequence(PageRequest.of(pageNum++, 1000));
            for (StoredEvent event : page) {
                applyEventToReadModel(event);
                processedCount++;
            }
            log.info("Rebuilt {} events", processedCount);
        } while (page.hasNext());

        log.info("Read model rebuild complete. Total events: {}", processedCount);
    }
}

// Run rebuild: POST /admin/rebuild-read-model
```

**With Kafka (events retained):**
```bash
# Reset consumer group offset to beginning — reprocess ALL events
kafka-consumer-groups.sh --bootstrap-server localhost:9092 \
  --group order-view-projector \
  --topic order.events \
  --reset-offsets --to-earliest --execute

# Output: New offset: 0 (will reprocess from the beginning)
```

Then restart the projector service — it replays every event and rebuilds the read model.

**This is why event retention in Kafka matters**: Set `retention.ms=-1` (infinite) or `retention.bytes=-1` for event-sourced topics so you can always rebuild.

An **aggregate** is a cluster of related objects treated as a single unit for data changes. It has a root entity (aggregate root), and all commands go through the root.

```java
// Order is an aggregate root
// All changes to OrderItems, OrderStatus, etc. go through Order
@Entity
public class Order {  // Aggregate root
    @Id
    private UUID id;
    private OrderStatus status;

    @OneToMany(cascade = CascadeType.ALL, orphanRemoval = true)
    private List<OrderItem> items;  // Part of the same aggregate

    // Business rules enforced at aggregate root level
    public void cancel(String reason) {
        if (status == OrderStatus.SHIPPED) {
            throw new BusinessException("Cannot cancel shipped order");
        }
        this.status = OrderStatus.CANCELLED;
        this.cancellationReason = reason;
    }

    public void addItem(Product product, int quantity) {
        if (status != OrderStatus.DRAFT) {
            throw new BusinessException("Cannot modify non-draft order");
        }
        items.add(new OrderItem(product, quantity));
    }
}
```

**Aggregates define transaction boundaries**:
- One transaction should modify at most one aggregate
- If you need to modify two aggregates → use events between them

**Relationship to CQRS**:
- Commands target a specific aggregate (by ID)
- The aggregate validates the command and publishes events
- Events update the read model

```text
Command: PlaceOrderCommand(orderId=abc)
  → Load Order aggregate (id=abc)
  → order.place() — validates business rules
  → publishes OrderPlacedEvent
  → ProjectionUpdater updates OrderView read model
```

**Liveness probe**: Is this container still functioning? Should Kubernetes restart it?
```text
Failing case: Deadlock in thread pool → container runs but can't process requests
Action on failure: Kubernetes RESTARTS the pod
Configure: longer initial delay (give Spring Boot time to start) and lenient failure threshold
```

**Readiness probe**: Is this pod ready to receive traffic? Should the load balancer route to it?
```text
Failing case: Spring Boot still initializing, or pod is waiting for DB connection
Action on failure: Kubernetes REMOVES pod from load balancer pool (no traffic)
No restart — just traffic isolation
```

```java
// Custom readiness indicator — report not ready until all deps are up
@Component
public class DatabaseReadinessIndicator implements ReadinessStateHealthIndicator {

    private final DataSource dataSource;

    @Override
    protected void doHealthCheck(Health.Builder builder) {
        try {
            dataSource.getConnection().close();
            builder.up();  // DB reachable → pod is READY
        } catch (SQLException e) {
            builder.outOfService()  // DB not ready → don't route traffic here yet
                .withDetail("error", e.getMessage());
        }
    }
}
```

**Startup probe** (third type, Spring Boot 2.3+):
```yaml
startupProbe:
  httpGet:
    path: /actuator/health/readiness
    port: 8080
  failureThreshold: 30   # allow 5 minutes to start (30 × 10s)
  periodSeconds: 10
# Once startup probe passes, Kubernetes enables readiness and liveness probes
```

Use startup probe for slow-starting applications — prevents liveness probe from killing a pod that's just taking a long time to initialize.

**Thundering herd**: A new pod becomes ready. The load balancer immediately sends it 100 requests. The pod isn't warmed up (JVM JIT not compiled, DB connection pool not warmed, caches empty) → pod is slow for first few seconds → load balancer might temporarily mark it unhealthy.

**Fix 1 — Slow start (NGINX):**
```nginx
upstream order_service {
    server pod-1:8080;
    server pod-2:8080;
    server pod-3:8080 slow_start=30s;  # gradually ramp up traffic over 30s
    # (commercial NGINX Plus only — not in open-source)
}
```

**Fix 2 — Pre-warm with Spring Boot ApplicationRunner:**
```java
@Component
@Order(1)  // runs during startup, before readiness probe passes
public class JvmWarmupRunner implements ApplicationRunner {

    private final ProductService productService;

    @Override
    public void run(ApplicationArguments args) throws Exception {
        log.info("Warming up JVM...");

        // Hit the critical code paths to trigger JIT compilation
        for (int i = 0; i < 100; i++) {
            try { productService.getProduct(1L); } catch (Exception e) {}
        }

        // Pre-warm DB connection pool
        dataSource.getConnection().close();

        log.info("Warmup complete — pod ready for traffic");
        // Now readiness probe will return UP and load balancer adds this pod
    }
}
```

**Fix 3 — JVM flags for faster warmup:**
```yaml
# K8s pod spec
env:
- name: JAVA_OPTS
  value: "-server -XX:+TieredCompilation -XX:TieredStopAtLevel=4"
# TieredCompilation = more aggressive JIT from start
```

