## Why this is hard

```text
Naive approach: "Let the instance with the highest IP be the leader"
  Problem: What if that instance is slow/overloaded but not crashed?
  Problem: What if there's a network partition — two groups think they're leader?
  That's the split-brain problem — two coordinators both assigning the same tasks → duplicates
```

---

## Approach 1: Redis-based leader election (simplest)

```java
@Component
@RequiredArgsConstructor
@Slf4j
public class LeaderElectionService {

    private final StringRedisTemplate redis;
    private final TaskCoordinator taskCoordinator;

    private static final String LEADER_KEY = "batch-service:leader";
    private static final long LEASE_TTL_SECONDS = 15;      // leader lease duration
    private static final long HEARTBEAT_INTERVAL_MS = 5000; // renew every 5s

    private final String instanceId = InetAddress.getLocalHost().getHostName()
        + ":" + UUID.randomUUID();

    private volatile boolean isLeader = false;
    private ScheduledExecutorService scheduler;

    @PostConstruct
    public void start() {
        scheduler = Executors.newSingleThreadScheduledExecutor();
        scheduler.scheduleAtFixedRate(this::tryAcquireOrRenewLeadership,
            0, HEARTBEAT_INTERVAL_MS, TimeUnit.MILLISECONDS);
    }

    private void tryAcquireOrRenewLeadership() {
        try {
            if (isLeader) {
                // Renew lease to stay leader
                Boolean renewed = redis.expire(LEADER_KEY, LEASE_TTL_SECONDS, TimeUnit.SECONDS);
                if (Boolean.FALSE.equals(renewed)) {
                    // Key expired before we could renew — we lost leadership (e.g., GC pause)
                    isLeader = false;
                    log.warn("[{}] Lost leadership — lease expired before renewal", instanceId);
                    onLeadershipLost();
                } else {
                    log.debug("[{}] Leadership lease renewed", instanceId);
                }
            } else {
                // Try to become leader
                Boolean acquired = redis.opsForValue().setIfAbsent(
                    LEADER_KEY, instanceId, LEASE_TTL_SECONDS, TimeUnit.SECONDS);

                if (Boolean.TRUE.equals(acquired)) {
                    isLeader = true;
                    log.info("[{}] Became LEADER", instanceId);
                    onLeadershipAcquired();
                } else {
                    // Someone else is leader — find out who
                    String currentLeader = redis.opsForValue().get(LEADER_KEY);
                    log.debug("[{}] Not leader. Current leader: {}", instanceId, currentLeader);
                }
            }
        } catch (Exception e) {
            log.error("[{}] Error in leader election", instanceId, e);
            if (isLeader) {
                isLeader = false;
                onLeadershipLost();
            }
        }
    }

    private void onLeadershipAcquired() {
        taskCoordinator.startCoordination();
    }

    private void onLeadershipLost() {
        taskCoordinator.stopCoordination();
    }

    public boolean isLeader() { return isLeader; }

    @PreDestroy
    public void shutdown() {
        scheduler.shutdown();
        if (isLeader) {
            // Release leadership when shutting down gracefully
            String current = redis.opsForValue().get(LEADER_KEY);
            if (instanceId.equals(current)) {
                redis.delete(LEADER_KEY);  // allows another instance to immediately take over
                log.info("[{}] Released leadership on shutdown", instanceId);
            }
        }
    }
}
```

**How the Redis key works:**
```bash
# Instance A acquires leadership:
redis-cli SET batch-service:leader "instance-A:uuid-123" EX 15 NX
# Returns: OK (acquired successfully)

# Instance B tries at the same time:
redis-cli SET batch-service:leader "instance-B:uuid-456" EX 15 NX
# Returns: nil (key already exists — instance A is leader)

# Instance A renews every 5s:
redis-cli EXPIRE batch-service:leader 15
# Returns: 1

# If instance A crashes — no renewal — key expires after 15s:
redis-cli TTL batch-service:leader
# Returns: 9  (9 seconds until expiry)
# After 15s: key gone

# Instance B's next heartbeat:
redis-cli SET batch-service:leader "instance-B:uuid-456" EX 15 NX
# Returns: OK (instance B is now leader!)
```

**Expected log output (3 instances, A becomes leader):**
```text
[instance-A:uuid-1] Became LEADER
[instance-A:uuid-1] Leadership lease renewed
[instance-A:uuid-1] Leadership lease renewed
[instance-B:uuid-2] Not leader. Current leader: instance-A:uuid-1
[instance-C:uuid-3] Not leader. Current leader: instance-A:uuid-1

# Instance A crashes — after 15 seconds:
[instance-B:uuid-2] Became LEADER  ← took over within 15s
[instance-C:uuid-3] Not leader. Current leader: instance-B:uuid-2
```

---

## Approach 2: Spring Integration Leader Election (ZooKeeper)

```xml
<dependency>
  <groupId>org.springframework.integration</groupId>
  <artifactId>spring-integration-zookeeper</artifactId>
  <version>6.2.0</version>
</dependency>
```

```java
@Configuration
public class LeaderElectionConfig {

    @Bean
    public CuratorFramework curatorFramework() {
        CuratorFramework client = CuratorFrameworkFactory.newClient(
            "zookeeper:2181",
            new ExponentialBackoffRetry(1000, 3));
        client.start();
        return client;
    }

    @Bean
    public LeaderInitiatorFactoryBean leaderInitiator(
            CuratorFramework curator) {
        return new LeaderInitiatorFactoryBean()
            .setClient(curator)
            .setPath("/batch-service/leader")  // ZooKeeper path for election
            .setRole("leader");
    }
}

// Listen for leadership events
@Component
@Slf4j
public class LeaderEventHandler implements ApplicationListener<AbstractLeaderEvent> {

    private final TaskCoordinator taskCoordinator;

    @Override
    public void onApplicationEvent(AbstractLeaderEvent event) {
        if (event instanceof OnGrantedEvent) {
            log.info("Leadership GRANTED to this instance");
            taskCoordinator.startCoordination();
        } else if (event instanceof OnRevokedEvent) {
            log.info("Leadership REVOKED from this instance");
            taskCoordinator.stopCoordination();
        }
    }
}
```

**How ZooKeeper leader election works:**
```text
All instances create ephemeral sequential znodes: /election/lock-0001, lock-0002, lock-0003
Instance with the LOWEST number = leader

If instance-A (lock-0001) crashes:
  ZooKeeper deletes its ephemeral node automatically (ZooKeeper detects session timeout)
  Instance-B (lock-0002) was watching lock-0001 → gets notified
  Instance-B sees it now has the lowest number → becomes leader
  Failover time: ZooKeeper session timeout (~5-10 seconds)
```

---

## Approach 3: Spring Integration with Redis (simpler than ZooKeeper)

```java
@Bean
public LeaderInitiatorFactoryBean redisLeader(
        RedisConnectionFactory connectionFactory) {
    return new LeaderInitiatorFactoryBean()
        .setConnectionFactory(connectionFactory)
        .setPath("batch-service:leader")
        .setHeartBeatMillis(5000)    // renew every 5s
        .setPublishFailedEvents(true);
}
```

Spring handles the lease renewal and leadership events automatically.

