## Your interview answer

> "Offset pagination does a full scan to discard skipped rows — at page 500 with size 50, PostgreSQL reads 25,050 rows to return 50. I switched to keyset pagination: instead of OFFSET, the query uses a WHERE clause that filters based on the last seen (created_at, id) pair. With a composite index on (user_id, created_at DESC, id DESC), this is a direct index seek — O(log N) regardless of page depth. The cursor is the Base64-encoded last item of each page. This also fixes the data-shift problem since the cursor anchors pagination to specific row values, not position numbers."

