**Page<T>**: Fetches items AND executes a COUNT query to know total pages.
```java
Page<Order> page = orderRepo.findByUserId(userId, PageRequest.of(0, 50));
// Executes TWO queries:
//   1. SELECT * FROM orders WHERE user_id=? LIMIT 50 OFFSET 0
//   2. SELECT COUNT(*) FROM orders WHERE user_id=?  ← expensive on large tables!
page.getTotalElements()  // total count (from query 2)
page.getTotalPages()     // total pages
page.hasNext()           // true/false
```

**Slice<T>**: Fetches items + 1 to detect if there's a next page — NO COUNT query.
```java
Slice<Order> slice = orderRepo.findByUserId(userId, PageRequest.of(0, 50));
// Executes ONE query: SELECT * FROM orders WHERE user_id=? LIMIT 51 OFFSET 0
// Returns 50 items (or fewer if no more data)
// Internally fetches 51 to check if there are more
slice.hasNext()  // true if 51 rows returned (more exist)
slice.hasNext()  // false if <= 50 rows returned
// NO total count available
```

**Repository method:**
```java
Slice<Order> findByUserId(Long userId, Pageable pageable);
// Spring sees return type Slice<T> → generates LIMIT (size+1), no COUNT
```

**When to use which:**
- **Page**: Admin tables that show "Showing 250 of 3,847 results", sortable/filterable grids
- **Slice**: Infinite scroll, mobile "load more" buttons, APIs where you only need hasNext

**Performance difference on 1M rows:**
```text
Page.getTotalElements(): COUNT(*) = 1.2 seconds on unindexed table
Slice.hasNext():         checks limit+1 = 0ms overhead
```

Dynamic filters + pagination is tricky because the cursor must remain valid when filters change.

**Problem with keyset pagination + dynamic filters:**
```text
User searches: GET /api/orders?status=PLACED&cursor=xyz
Query: WHERE user_id=? AND status='PLACED' AND (created_at < ?, id < ?)

User changes filter to status=CANCELLED → existing cursor is from PLACED orders
→ cursor is meaningless for the new filter
→ Must restart from page 1 when filter changes
```

**Spring Data Specifications for dynamic filters:**
```java
@Service
public class OrderSearchService {

    public PageResponse<Order> search(OrderSearchFilter filter) {
        // Build dynamic WHERE clause
        Specification<Order> spec = Specification.where(null);

        if (filter.getStatus() != null) {
            spec = spec.and((root, query, cb) ->
                cb.equal(root.get("status"), filter.getStatus()));
        }
        if (filter.getFromDate() != null) {
            spec = spec.and((root, query, cb) ->
                cb.greaterThanOrEqualTo(root.get("createdAt"), filter.getFromDate()));
        }
        if (filter.getMinAmount() != null) {
            spec = spec.and((root, query, cb) ->
                cb.greaterThanOrEqualTo(root.get("totalAmount"), filter.getMinAmount()));
        }

        // Add keyset cursor condition if not first page
        if (filter.getCursor() != null) {
            CursorPosition pos = decodeCursor(filter.getCursor());
            Specification<Order> cursorSpec = (root, query, cb) -> cb.or(
                cb.lessThan(root.get("createdAt"), pos.getLastTs()),
                cb.and(
                    cb.equal(root.get("createdAt"), pos.getLastTs()),
                    cb.lessThan(root.get("id"), pos.getLastId())
                )
            );
            spec = spec.and(cursorSpec);
        }

        Sort sort = Sort.by(
            Sort.Order.desc("createdAt"),
            Sort.Order.desc("id")
        );
        Pageable pageable = PageRequest.of(0, filter.getLimit() + 1, sort);

        Slice<Order> results = orderRepo.findAll(spec, pageable);
        // ... build response with next cursor
    }
}
```

**Rule**: Reset to page 1 whenever the filter changes (new cursor starts from the beginning of the filtered result set). Frontend should clear the cursor when the user changes any filter.

