## Step 3: DLT consumer for inspection and replay

```java
// DLT messages have headers explaining why they failed
@Component
@Slf4j
public class OrderEventDltConsumer {

    private final DlqMessageRepository dlqRepo;
    private final AlertingService alerting;

    @KafkaListener(
        topics = "order.events.DLT",
        groupId = "order-dlq-inspector"
    )
    public void handleDlt(
            @Payload String payload,
            @Headers MessageHeaders headers) {

        // Spring Kafka adds these headers automatically
        String originalTopic = headers.get(
            KafkaHeaders.DLT_ORIGINAL_TOPIC, String.class);
        String exceptionMessage = headers.get(
            KafkaHeaders.DLT_EXCEPTION_MESSAGE, String.class);
        String exceptionClass = headers.get(
            KafkaHeaders.DLT_EXCEPTION_FQCN, String.class);
        Long originalOffset = headers.get(
            KafkaHeaders.DLT_ORIGINAL_OFFSET, Long.class);

        log.warn("DLT message received: originalTopic={} offset={} error={}",
            originalTopic, originalOffset, exceptionMessage);

        // Save for manual inspection and potential replay
        dlqRepo.save(DlqMessage.builder()
            .payload(payload)
            .originalTopic(originalTopic)
            .originalOffset(originalOffset)
            .exceptionClass(exceptionClass)
            .exceptionMessage(exceptionMessage)
            .receivedAt(Instant.now())
            .status(DlqStatus.PENDING_REVIEW)
            .build());

        // Alert engineering team for non-retriable errors
        if (exceptionClass != null && exceptionClass.contains("JsonParseException")) {
            alerting.sendSlackAlert(
                "Malformed JSON in order.events — manual fix required. Offset: " + originalOffset);
        }
    }
}
```

