**RabbitMQ Dead Letter Exchange (DLX):**

```java
// RabbitMQ: configure DLX at queue creation
@Bean
public Queue orderQueue() {
    return QueueBuilder.durable("order.queue")
        .withArgument("x-dead-letter-exchange", "order.dlx")  // where failures go
        .withArgument("x-dead-letter-routing-key", "order.dlq")  // routing key in DLX
        .withArgument("x-message-ttl", 60000)  // optional: expire after 60s
        .build();
}

@Bean
public DirectExchange deadLetterExchange() {
    return new DirectExchange("order.dlx");
}

@Bean
public Queue deadLetterQueue() {
    return QueueBuilder.durable("order.dlq").build();
}

@Bean
public Binding dlqBinding() {
    return BindingBuilder.bind(deadLetterQueue())
        .to(deadLetterExchange())
        .with("order.dlq");
}
```

**RabbitMQ DLX automatic routing:**
- Message is nacked (consumer calls `channel.basicNack(deliveryTag, false, false)`)
- OR message TTL expires
- OR queue length limit exceeded
- → Automatically routed to DLX → DLQ

**Key differences:**
```text
Kafka DLT:                         RabbitMQ DLQ:
  Explicit: ErrorHandler sends to DLT   Automatic: broker routes on nack
  Message retained (log compaction)     Message moved (original is gone)
  Order within partition preserved      No ordering guarantee
  Replay = re-publish to topic          Replay = move from DLQ to main queue
  Multiple consumers can replay         Single consumer per queue
  Requires replay code                  Can use RabbitMQ Management UI to move
```

**RabbitMQ retry pattern (using plugins):**
